    text: "## Pharmacokinetics: The Drug's Journey\n\nWhen a medication is swallowed, it must go through four distinct phases before it can be removed from the body: Absorption, Distribution, Metabolism, and Excretion (ADME).\n\nAbsorption is how the drug gets into the blood. Oral medications must survive the highly acidic stomach and pass through the intestinal wall. Distribution is how the drug travels. Most drugs attach themselves to proteins in the blood, primarily Albumin, which act as vehicles to carry the drug throughout the body. \n\nMetabolism is how the body breaks the drug down, and this occurs almost entirely in the liver. Excretion is how the drug is physically removed, primarily filtered out by the kidneys and expelled in the urine.\n\n[[[The most critical barrier in this journey is the liver. When a pill is absorbed through the stomach, the blood vessels carry it directly to the liver first. The liver acts as a harsh filter, breaking down and destroying a massive portion of the drug. This is called the [[First-Pass Effect]].]]]\n\n[PAGE]\n\n## Bioavailability and Routes of Administration\n\nBecause the liver destroys so much of an oral pill, only a fraction of the drug actually makes it to the heart to be pumped to the rest of the body. This remaining, usable percentage is called [[Bioavailability]].\n\n{{In medical emergencies, waiting for a pill to digest and losing half of the dose to the liver is not acceptable. This is why the Intravenous (IV) route is used. By injecting the drug directly into the vein, the stomach and liver are completely bypassed. Therefore, IV medications have 100% Bioavailability and act almost instantly.}}\n\nOther routes avoid the liver as well. Sublingual medications (placed under the tongue) absorb directly into the rich blood vessels of the mouth, bypassing the stomach and liver entirely. \n\n[PAGE]\n\n## Pharmacodynamics: How Drugs Work\n\nOnce a drug is in the bloodstream, it must alter the body's function. Cells have specific receptors on their surface, functioning exactly like locks. The drug acts as a key.\n\nIf the drug fits perfectly into the receptor, unlocks it, and turns the cell's function ON, it is called an Agonist. For example, an asthma inhaler acts as an agonist, telling the lung cells to open wide. \n\nIf the drug fits into the receptor but does not turn the cell on, it simply blocks the keyhole. This prevents the body's natural chemicals from entering. This is called an Antagonist. A blood pressure medication is an antagonist; it blocks adrenaline from entering the heart, preventing the heart from racing.\n\n[[[To safely dose medications, nurses must understand the [[Half-Life]]. If a drug has a half-life of 4 hours, the body will eliminate exactly half of the drug every 4 hours. A 100mg dose becomes 50mg at 4 hours, and 25mg at 8 hours. If the next dose is given too early, before the drug has cleared, the levels will stack and cause fatal toxicity.]]]"
